metadata.name: Magic Board II #108
metadata.description:
When the ratio of two quantities is equal to the ratio of their sum to the larger quantity, there is a golden ratio in geometric patterns, and this property can create different geometric shapes.
The points are all randomly placed in each design, and the placement of these shapes together creates the impression of a geometric pattern based on random processing.
There is no end to these geometric patterns.
press 's' to save original size

metadata.name: Rimal #210
metadata.description:
A manifestation of elemental simplicity and tactile potential, the abstract sand plate transcends its granular composition to embody a realm of dynamic abstraction. As a textured canvas, it defies permanence, inviting fluidity and transformation in response to the whims of creation, science, therapy, and education.

In the artistic spectrum, the abstract sand plate becomes an ever-shifting tableau where the interplay of hands orchestrates ephemeral masterpieces. Here, the grains of sand, liberated from fixity, participate in an intricate dance of form and impermanence, blurring the lines between creation and dissolution.

[s] to save image

metadata.name: Timing #139
metadata.description:
Time.. 
While one thing happens one time, another happens several times.

----------------------------------------------------------------
  Keys control:
    r: toggle rotation
    i: increment rotation speed
    d: decrement rotation speed
    p: toggle show points
    s: save current size image to .png
    x + 2/4/8: save 2x/4x/8x size image to .png
    1-9 + g: save 1-9 sec animation to .gif (depends on the machine resources)

  URL parameters:
    fps=<value>: frame rate
    r=true: rotation ON
    p=false: do not show points

metadata.name: Charcoal Landscapes #44
metadata.description:
This work is an exploration of abstract landscapes using lines that are bounded to 8 directions. This limitation still allows for somewhat organic visuals and creates a visual language more akin to traditional drawing techniques.

Using a vector field with a noise function at different scales, I construct paths starting at random positions and moving to the neighbours cells pointed at by the vector field. Paths have a limitation of length and are bounded to the grid. I create tens of thousands of paths then render progressively on screen.

There are 10 parameters variations and 4 colors, 2 being rare and one very rare.

Original artwork by William Watkins · Lyon, 2021

metadata.name: Geometric Motion #31
metadata.description:
Inspired by minimalist graphic designs, this work is an exploration of combinations for simple geometrical shapes. The shapes slide under others, go out of view and reappear in an ever-changing canvas.

On a grid of 4 to 7 cells we place triangles, squares, and circles of different sizes. Their color and draw order are determined by their initial row placement. They move around freely inside the canvas indefinitely, showing a quasi-infinite number of combinations.

There are 10 possible colors, with 2 that are very rare that change the blend method to "exclusion" or "difference".

Coded with p5js

Original artwork by William Watkins · Lyon, 2021
